hacktheplanet — CTF / HackTheBox / authorized-engagement command reference
==========================================================================
The field reference that sits under OFFENSIVE-METHODOLOGY.md. That doc is the
high-altitude phase -> MITRE ATT&CK -> tool MAP; this file is the opposite
altitude: concrete copy-paste command syntax, per service / per port.

Originally my "Home-Directory" notes file, since expanded with field techniques
from TrustedSec's "Actionable Purple Teaming" course (Black Hat USA 2023). The
DEFENSIVE half of that course — the Splunk/Sentinel detections each attack trips
— lives in the companion PURPLE-TEAM.md at the repo root. It folds in vim/neovim: each section
is wrapped in marker banners (the modeline at the very bottom wires foldmethod
so the folds work with no extra config — open with `vim hacktheplanet`, toggle a
fold with `za`, close all with `zM`, open all with `zR`).

SCOPE FIRST. Every command below is for AUTHORIZED engagements (written ROE +
defined scope) or your own CTF / HTB lab boxes. Installing a tool is not
permission to point it at anything. Engagement DATA never lives in this repo —
it lives in ~/engagements (see `mkengagement`).

Target fill: drop your box's details once, then every <placeholder> below is
real. In vim, run the recorded macro (mark x, substitute, jump back):
    mx
    :%s,<ip_address>,10.10.10.10,g
    :%s,<hostname>,box.htb,g
    :%s,<domain>,corp.local,g
    'x
...or just :%s them by hand. These five are the recurring TARGET identifiers the
macro is worth running for:
    <ip_address>  <hostname>  <domain>  <user>  <password>
Other placeholders are per-command one-offs you fill inline, NOT via the macro —
notably <your-ip> (YOUR attacker/listener IP, never the target's), plus things
like <port>, <NThash>, <share>, <rid>/<sid>, <internal-ip>.


Scanning
++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
# Quick + thorough TCP, then targeted. (`nmapsweep` in offensive.zsh wraps #1.)
sudo nmap -sC -sV -oA <hostname>_1-initial <ip_address>
sudo nmap -sC -sV -sU -oA <hostname>_2-udp <ip_address>
sudo nmap -p- -T4 --min-rate 10000 -oA <hostname>_3-tcp-discovery <ip_address>
sudo nmap -A -p <ports> -oA <hostname>_4-tcp-full-scan <ip_address>   # <ports> = comma-separated list from the discovery scan

# Fast port discovery when nmap -p- is slow:
rustscan -a <ip_address> --ulimit 5000 -- -sC -sV
masscan -p1-65535 <ip_address> --rate 10000 -oL masscan.txt

# Always add the box to /etc/hosts so vhosts/Kerberos resolve:
echo "<ip_address> <hostname> <domain>" | sudo tee -a /etc/hosts
